stylometry: When managing inventory the whole idea is to figure out how to provide enough inventory to cover the demand of the product without increasing inventory costs.  If the inventory manager orders too much inventory and the demand is not high enough for the amount of inventory ordered, then they face inventory costs based on holding costs, set-up costs, and production costs.  If the manager orders too much of a product, they need a place to store all of the extra inventory (e.g. in a warehouse, taking up shelving space, rent costs etc.) and that will cost them more money.  In several situations there is a set-up or ordering cost for every inventory order placed on top of the actual dollar amount of the products being purchased so the inventory manager needs to figure out the lowest amount of orders they can place per year while also making sure they don't accumulate too much inventory that they can't sell.  Clothing stores will most likely be able to make fewer orders in a year based on the season of their clothing.  However, restaurants and grocery stores will have to make several more orders because their products are perishable and if they order too much in a short amount of time and there is not a high enough demand, they can lose money because of expiration dates.  On the other hand, management needs to make sure they purchase enough inventory to satisfy the demand of their customers.  If a company orders their inventory on a Monday and it is delivered on a Thursday, they have 3 days of lead time and they need to make sure they have enough safety stock to cover the demand before the next order makes it to their store.  There are also unforeseen circumstances that can occur during deliveries so that needs to be taken into account when a company purchases inventory.  If they do not have the inventory in stock when a customer comes to purchase, they are losing revenue.
